<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1260,2005]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1260,1285]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Ventral color white, with a distinct line of demarcation (
<figureCitation box="[912,1025,1260,1285]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="19.[151,250,886,908]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,267,862]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[264,1323,267,862]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 18. The gray hamster, Cricetulus migratorius (photo by Adwan Shehab)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202813/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figure 18</figureCitation>
). Fur is soft and woolly, on the back gray to grayish-brown with a distinct dark stripe along the middle of the back. Cheek pouches present. Tail is less than one-third of body length. Four pairs of mammae. Skull small, with small tympanic bullae. Very distinctive for this species is that the teeth consist of parallel rows of cusps (
<figureCitation box="[838,951,1368,1393]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1998,2020]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,958,1977]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[264,1323,958,1977]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 19. A. Dorsal,B. Ventral,C. Lateral views of the skull, and D. Upper maxillary teeth for Cricetulus migratorius." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202815/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figure 19</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1260,2005]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,553,1404,1429]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Localities: Previous records.</emphasis>
